Author-Name: Jean-Sébastien Marcoux 
Title: Escaping the Gift Economy 
Abstract:
 Researchers have analyzed the dark side of the gift, but they have
 remained blind to what it implies about the market. Drawing on the
 experiences of a group of informants who participated in an ethnographical
 study of house moving in Montreal, Canada, this article provides
 significant evidence that the unattractiveness of the gift economy can
 incite people to turn to the market as an escape. It examines how people
 use the market to free themselves from the straitjacket of social
 expectations-from the sense of indebtedness and emotional oppression-which
 constrains them in their reciprocity relations inside the gift economy.
 The standard views of CCT researchers concerning the valorization of the
 gift economy are challenged, as well as the axiology that implicitly
 informs their research. As a result, it is necessary to discuss the
 inversion of this axiology. (c) 2009 by JOURNAL OF CONSUMER RESEARCH, Inc.. 
